4 Concepts
**********

4.1 Tokens
==========

Every constructor returns a “token” -- a ‘pending’ struct used as a
handle for the placeholder.  Pass the token to ‘pending-finish’,
‘pending-cancel’, ‘pending-update’, and friends to operate on the
placeholder.

   Tokens are valid until they reach a terminal state.  Operations on a
terminal token are no-ops with a ‘:debug’ warning.

   The lifecycle states are:

‘:scheduled’
     The placeholder has been created but no work has begun (or the
     caller has not yet sent any signal).

‘:running’
     The caller has indicated that work is in progress.  This state is
     reserved for future use; current call-sites typically transition
     directly from ‘:scheduled’ to ‘:streaming’ or to a terminal state.

‘:streaming’
     At least one chunk has been delivered via ‘pending-stream-insert’.
     The end marker's insertion-type is ‘t’, so subsequent chunks append
     at the end naturally.

‘:resolved’
     Terminal.  The placeholder's region has been replaced with the
     final content.

‘:rejected’
     Terminal.  The placeholder failed; the region carries an error
     glyph plus reason.

‘:cancelled’
     Terminal.  The user (or library) cancelled the placeholder; the
     region carries a small cancelled glyph.

‘:expired’
     Terminal.  Reserved for future use.

   ‘pending-active-p’ returns non-nil for the first three states
(‘:scheduled’, ‘:running’, ‘:streaming’); the others are terminal.

4.2 The pending registry
========================

All active placeholders are recorded in a global registry.  Two public
functions surface it:

‘pending-alist’
     Returns ‘((ID . STRUCT) ...)’ for every registered placeholder,
     including terminal ones still in transit.  Order is unspecified;
     the alist is fresh and safe to mutate.

‘pending-list-active’
     Returns a list of structs in active states only.  Accepts optional
     ‘BUFFER’ and ‘GROUP’ filters.

   The registry is also the data source for ‘M-x pending-list’ and the
mode-line lighter.

4.3 Lighter vs region highlight
===============================

The library distinguishes two visual treatments:

*Region highlight*
     When the overlay covers existing buffer text (adopt mode
     ‘pending-region BEG END STR’ with ‘BEG < END’), the overlay carries
     ‘pending-highlight’ as its ‘face’ property so the user can see
     _which_ characters the asynchronous change will rewrite.  In insert
     mode and zero-width adopt mode the overlay has no face -- there is
     no pre-existing region to highlight.

*Lighter*
     A small bold badge (face ‘pending-lighter’) attached to the
     overlay's ‘before-string’.  This is the prominent visual marker
     that draws the eye.

   The simple API uses a static lighter (‘:lighter’ indicator).  The
rich API can substitute an animated spinner, a determinate bar, or an
ETA bar in place of the static lighter.

   The library NEVER applies a ‘face’ text property to text it inserts
itself: labels, streamed chunks, and resolution / rejection /
cancellation replacement text all land in the buffer as plain text, so
the surrounding font-lock and major-mode faces apply normally.  Only the
overlay (in adopt mode with a non-empty range) and the overlay's
‘before-string’ lighter / ‘after-string’ progress bar are faced.

4.4 Read-only protection
========================

While a placeholder is active, its inserted text is read-only via text
properties:

   • ‘read-only t’
   • ‘front-sticky '(read-only)’ so insertions just before the
     placeholder are blocked.
   • ‘rear-nonsticky '(read-only)’ so insertions just after it are
     allowed.

   The user can edit before and after the placeholder freely, but not
the placeholder body itself.  The library binds ‘inhibit-read-only’
during its own operations so internal swaps still work.

   In adopt mode (‘pending-make’ with explicit ‘:start’ and ‘:end’), the
library does _not_ retroactively add read-only properties -- the caller
owns that text.

4.5 Auto-cancellation paths
===========================

Several edge conditions auto-cancel an in-flight placeholder so it
cannot strand state:

*Region deletion*
     If the user deletes the entire placeholder region, the overlay
     collapses to zero length and a ‘modification-hook’ cancels with
     reason ‘:region-deleted’.

*Buffer kill*
     ‘kill-buffer-hook’ iterates the buffer's pending registry and
     cancels each with reason ‘:buffer-killed’.

*Deadline*
     When ‘pending-make’ is called with ‘:deadline N’, a one-shot timer
     fires ‘pending-reject’ with reason ‘:timed-out’ if the placeholder
     is still active after N seconds.

*Process death*
     ‘pending-attach-process’ wraps the process sentinel; if the process
     dies non-cleanly (or cleanly without an explicit resolve), the
     placeholder is rejected with a reason derived from
     ‘process-status’.

*Emacs exit*
     When ‘pending-confirm-on-emacs-exit’ is non-nil and active
     placeholders exist, ‘kill-emacs-query-functions’ prompts before
     exit.


