6 Rich API
**********

The rich keyword API provides full control: streaming, animation, ETA
bars, deadlines, and process attachment.

 -- Function: pending-make buffer &key label start end indicator
          deadline eta percent face spinner-style on-cancel on-resolve
          group
     The full constructor.  Inserts (or adopts) a placeholder in BUFFER.
     Returns the new ‘pending’ struct.

     Insertion modes:

     *Insert mode*
          If both START and END are nil, insert a new placeholder at
          point in BUFFER. The inserted label text is propertized
          read-only.

     *Adopt mode*
          If both START and END are non-nil (positions or markers),
          adopt the existing region ‘[START, END]’; do not insert text.
          Adopt mode does NOT retroactively add read-only properties to
          the existing text; the caller owns that text.

     It is an error to supply only one of START or END.

     Keyword          Meaning
     --------------------------------------------------------------------------
     ‘:label’         Short string shown inside the placeholder.  Default
                      ‘Pending’.
                      
     ‘:start’         Adopt mode endpoints (positions or markers).  Both or
     ‘:end’           neither.
                      
     ‘:indicator’     ‘:spinner’ (default), ‘:percent’, ‘:eta’, or
                      ‘:lighter’ (static badge).
                      
     ‘:percent’       Initial fraction in ‘[0.0, 1.0]’ for ‘:percent’ mode.
                      
     ‘:eta’           Estimated total seconds for ‘:eta’ mode.
                      
     ‘:deadline’      Wall-clock seconds until auto-rejection with reason
                      ‘:timed-out’.
                      
     ‘:face’          Override ‘pending-face’ for the OVERLAY's ‘face’
                      property in adopt mode (BEG < END only).  Inserted
                      text is never faced by the library.
                      
     ‘:spinner-style’ Key into ‘pending-spinner-styles’.
                      
     ‘:on-cancel’     Function ‘(P)’ called _before_ the cancellation
                      pipeline.  Abort underlying work here.
                      
     ‘:on-resolve’    Function ‘(P)’ called once on transition to any
                      terminal state.
                      
     ‘:group’         Symbol for filtering via ‘pending-list-active’.

     Side effects: inserts placeholder text (insert mode), creates and
     adopts an overlay, registers the struct, optionally schedules the
     deadline timer, and installs the buffer-kill hook locally.  Signals
     ‘pending-error’ on invalid arguments or a dead/read-only buffer.

          (pending-make (current-buffer)
                        :label "Calling Claude"
                        :indicator :spinner
                        :on-cancel (lambda (_) (gptel-abort)))

 -- Function: pending-update p &key label percent eta indicator
     Mutate slots mid-flight without changing state.  Useful when the
     caller learns more about progress -- e.g.  switch from ‘:spinner’
     to ‘:percent’ once the total work size is known.

     Clears the spinner-glyph render cache so any indicator/style
     changes apply on the next tick.  No-op (with debug warning) if P is
     in a terminal state.

          (pending-update tok :percent 0.42)
          (pending-update tok :indicator :eta :eta 10.0)

 -- Function: pending-stream-insert p chunk
     Append CHUNK (a string) to P's region.  The spinner / progress
     indicator stays visible.

     On the first chunk (when P is ‘:scheduled’ or ‘:running’) the
     loading-label content is deleted and replaced by CHUNK, the end
     marker's insertion-type is flipped to t, and the status transitions
     to ‘:streaming’.  Subsequent chunks append at the end marker, which
     advances with the insert because of its insertion-type.

     Streamed text gets the same read-only properties as the initial
     label, but no ‘face’ property: the library never faces text it
     inserts itself, so the buffer's normal font-lock applies.  The
     library binds ‘inhibit-read-only’ and ‘inhibit-modification-hooks’
     so its own inserts do not retrigger the cancel-on-collapse hook.

     This does NOT finalize.  The caller must follow up with
     ‘pending-stream-finish’, ‘pending-reject’, or ‘pending-cancel’.

     If P is already terminal, this is a no-op (debug warning); the
     chunk is dropped.  Signals ‘wrong-type-argument’ if CHUNK is not a
     string; an empty string is a no-op.

          (pending-stream-insert tok "Once upon a time, ")
          (pending-stream-insert tok "in a faraway land...")

 -- Function: pending-stream-finish p
     Finalize a streamed placeholder.  Transitions P from ‘:streaming’
     to ‘:resolved’.  Locks the end marker, strips read-only properties
     from the streamed region (so the resolved text becomes editable),
     removes the overlay's animated decorations, deletes the overlay,
     unregisters P, and fires its ‘:on-resolve’ callback.

     If P is ‘:scheduled’ or ‘:running’ (no chunks were ever streamed),
     behaves like ‘(pending-finish P "")’.  If P is already terminal, a
     no-op with debug warning.

          (pending-stream-finish tok)

 -- Function: pending-reject p reason &optional replacement-text
     Mark P as failed with REASON and replace its region.  REASON should
     be a string or a keyword/symbol describing the failure.
     REPLACEMENT-TEXT defaults to a glyph plus the reason.  The inserted
     text is plain -- the library never adds a ‘face’ property to text
     it inserts itself; surrounding font-lock applies normally.

     Side effects mirror ‘pending-finish’ (removes overlay, clears
     markers, unregisters, cancels timer, runs ‘:on-resolve’).

          (pending-reject tok "API rate limit exceeded")
          (pending-reject tok :network-down "Try again later.")

 -- Function: pending-attach-process p process
     Wire PROCESS so its death rejects P appropriately.  The process's
     existing sentinel, if any, is preserved: it runs first, then a
     wrapper inspects ‘process-status’ and calls ‘pending-reject’ on
     non-clean exit.  The reason is derived from the live process
     status, which is robust against localized event strings.

     Behaviour by status:

     ‘exit (code 0)’
          If P is still active, reject with ‘process exited without
          resolving’.

     ‘exit (non-zero)’
          Reject with ‘process: exited with code N’.

     ‘signal’
          Reject with ‘process: killed (signal N)’.

     ‘failed’
          Reject with ‘process: failed’.

     ‘closed’
          Reject with ‘process: connection closed’.

     ‘run / open / stop / listen / connect’
          No-op; the placeholder remains active.

     If multiple processes are attached over P's lifetime, the LAST
     attach wins for the ‘attached-process’ slot, but each prior
     process's wrapper still chains through.  A stale process exit will
     still flow into ‘pending-reject’, which is a no-op once P is
     terminal because of the single-resolution guard.

          (let ((proc (start-process "build" nil "make")))
            (pending-attach-process tok proc))

 -- Function: pending-active-p p
     Return non-nil if P is in an active (non-terminal) lifecycle state.
     The active states are ‘:scheduled’, ‘:running’, and ‘:streaming’.

 -- Function: pending-status p
     Return P's current status keyword.

 -- Function: pending-at &optional pos buffer
     Return the pending struct at POS in BUFFER, or nil if none.  POS
     defaults to point; BUFFER defaults to the current buffer.  Searches
     the overlays at POS for one carrying a ‘pending’ property.

 -- Function: pending-list-active &optional buffer group
     Return the list of active pending structs.  Optional BUFFER and
     GROUP filter the result.  Order within the result is unspecified.


