11 Customization
****************

11.1 User options
=================

 -- User Option: pending-fps
     Animation rate of pending placeholders, in frames per second.  Used
     by the single global animation timer that walks the registry on
     each tick.  A value of 10 (default) is the conventional sweet spot
     for in-buffer spinners -- fast enough to read as motion, slow
     enough not to hammer redisplay.

 -- User Option: pending-bar-width
     Width of the textual progress bar, in cells.  Default 16.  Used by
     the ‘:percent’ and ‘:eta’ indicators.

 -- User Option: pending-default-spinner-style
     Default key into ‘pending-spinner-styles’ for new placeholders.
     Default ‘'dots-1’.  Per-placeholder override available via the
     ‘:spinner-style’ keyword to ‘pending-make’.

 -- User Option: pending-spinner-styles
     Alist mapping spinner style symbols to vectors of frame strings.
     Built-in styles: ‘dots-1’, ‘dots-2’, ‘line’, ‘arc’, ‘clock’.  Add
     your own with ‘add-to-list’.

 -- User Option: pending-bar-style
     Bar character set: ‘eighths’ (Unicode eighth-block characters,
     default) or ‘ascii’ (ASCII fallback for terminals where Unicode
     block elements don't render).

 -- User Option: pending-bar-family
     Font family used for the progress bar segment, or nil.  When
     non-nil, the bar text is rendered in this family so that
     proportional buffer faces do not break alignment.  When nil, the
     bar inherits the surrounding face -- variable-pitch users may then
     see misalignment.

 -- User Option: pending-allow-read-only
     If non-nil, allow placement of placeholders in read-only buffers.
     By default ‘pending-make’ refuses to operate on a buffer where
     ‘buffer-read-only’ is non-nil; setting this to t binds
     ‘inhibit-read-only’ during insertion and resolution.  Useful for
     hosts like ‘compilation-mode’ or chat buffers that flip read-only
     on the caller's behalf.

 -- User Option: pending-label-max-width
     Maximum width, in characters, of a placeholder's visible label.
     Default 60.  Labels longer than this are truncated with an
     ellipsis; the full label remains available in the placeholder's
     tooltip.

 -- User Option: pending-confirm-on-emacs-exit
     If non-nil, prompt before exiting Emacs while placeholders are
     active.  Implemented via ‘pending--kill-emacs-query’, which is
     registered on ‘kill-emacs-query-functions’ at load time.  When nil
     (the default) the query function returns t unconditionally and the
     exit is not blocked.

11.2 Faces
==========

The library never adds a ‘face’ text property to text it inserts itself.
Faces are applied only to overlay properties -- the overlay's ‘face’
(when adopting an existing region with ‘BEG < END’), the overlay's
‘before-string’ lighter, and the overlay's ‘after-string’ progress bar.
This means the surrounding buffer's font-lock is never disturbed by the
placeholder library.

 -- Face: pending-highlight
     The overlay ‘face’ for adopt-mode placeholders that cover existing
     buffer text (‘BEG < END’).  In insert mode and zero-width adopt
     mode the overlay carries no face.  The library never applies this
     (or any) face as a text property to text it inserts itself.

 -- Face: pending-lighter
     Static badge shown at BEG of a pending overlay.  Bold white-on-red
     by default for high visibility.  The lighter is a visual badge
     attached to the overlay's ‘before-string’, not text in the buffer.

 -- Face: pending-face
     Default value of ‘pending-make’'s ‘:face’ keyword.  Inherits from
     ‘pending-highlight’.  Used as the overlay's ‘face’ property only
     when the overlay covers existing buffer text (adopt mode with a
     non-empty range).

 -- Face: pending-spinner-face
     The before-string spinner glyph.

 -- Face: pending-progress-face
     The after-string progress bar and ETA text.  Apply
     ‘pending-bar-family’ on top of this face when set, to keep
     alignment under variable-pitch buffer faces.

 -- Face: pending-error-face
     Retained for backward compatibility and customization.  As of
     v0.1.0 the library does not face inserted text -- ‘pending-reject’
     inserts plain buffer text and surrounding font-lock applies.

 -- Face: pending-cancelled-face
     Retained for backward compatibility and customization.  As of
     v0.1.0 the library does not face inserted text -- ‘pending-cancel’
     inserts plain buffer text and surrounding font-lock applies.


